{
  "text": "Some genomic information will moreover doubtlessly be of direct interest for the study of aquatic microbial populations in situ. Emerging techniques such as a combined FISH staining of mRNA and rRNA [CITATION_1] will allow us to detect the expression of metabolic genes within bacterioplankton populations defined at the level of single ecotypes [CITATION_2] . Ideally, such genespecific probing could be applied in combination with other ecologically relevant features of bacterial cells, e.g., morphology (223), proliferation [CITATION_3] , substrate uptake and turnover [CITATION_4] , motility [CITATION_5] , exoenzyme activity [CITATION_6] , or polysaccharide sheath formation [CITATION_7] . Moreover, a more complete knowledge of microbial genomes will allow us to detect far more subtle phylogenetic differences between bacteria than what can presently be derived from the analysis of 16S rRNA genes [CITATION_8] . Questions addressing the biogeography [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] and physiological or evolutionary adaptation of microbial ecotypes [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] might therefore form another area of future research in environmental microbiology.",
  "correct_citation": {
